Truth, I was living my life convinced it was never the right place or the right time to do anything, always subconsciously delaying to prevent myself from the potential of failure. 

When we finally decided to move I remember being like, okay fresh start perfect time to start, yet I became comfortable here and found more reasons to delay. 

And I’m realizing, there will always be more to learn and maybe even a better place or time to be, but we have no guarantees in life. If failure is what I may feel because I was finally brave enough to really commit to something, to really try, I’m not afraid of it anymore. 

So this December, I give myself the permission not only start, but to finish, to commit. I give myself the permission to be fearless. I hope you will too 🧡

LET’S TALK WELLNESS TRENDS FROM A TRAINER POV 🎤 In a world with a lot of noise and overwhelming information on the “best” way to live, I personally like to keep things simple. Focus on how you feel (energy level, mood, + performance) and prioritize movement, supporting your nervous system, mental health, and eat real whole foods 🍊

Pre-workout can have a lot of hidden sugar and a laundry list of chemicals. I personally have coffee and a snack like a date or banana and some nut butter to help me feel energized — also @athleticgreens and @drinklmnt or just coconut water are amazing options to energize you with nutrients and electrolytes. There are certainly some cleaner pre-workout options out there, but be careful not to become too reliant or out of touch with what you need, sleep is important too 😴 

Detox teas are a scam 🙅‍♀️ but I do love the use of ginger or peppermint teas to aid in digestion. If you’re looking to flush out toxins in your system, try lymphatic massages (s/o @misslymph ), dry brushing, saunas, incorporating chlorella supplements, hot water with lemon, @therabody jetboots and legs up the wall are amazing options to optimize your wellness routine! 

Consistency and sustainability over quick results when it comes to nourishing our body! This is your one your home, so you have to be in it for the long-haul. Everyone responds to food differently and I can only speak from my own experience. I prioritize real whole foods and a high protein diet with healthy fats and complex carbs. I do my best to avoid anything I’ve noticed causes inflammation (allergies, eczema, bloating, acne) and always have @arrae.co on hand 🙋‍♀️

SMASH — In creating @korebyremy I had to really reflect on when my body and mind felt the best, and don’t get me wrong I love high intensity and lifting heavy weights and there are so many benefits, but I’m in the era of listening to what my body needs vs pushing myself to work harder and harder for longer and longer. I am loving low impact workouts that prioritize a strong core and mind-body connection — plus @bala bangles make every workout more fun!

social_posts.post_text: I’ve been trying find all my favorite pics from our trip to The Caribbean (and an impromptu trip to Miami) and end up not posting anything, so here are some bits and pieces of sunshine 🏝️🍊🧡☀️✨

Some thoughts of mine from an emotional roller coaster of a week 🎢😆🙏🦋❤️‍🩹

I used to think wellness was working out for hours a day EVERY SINGLE DAY, staying away from “bad” foods, choosing fitness over social events, and never having dessert or sleeping in. 

Now—wellness is daily movement of whatever feels good, making time for old friends, drinking wine and slumber parties, real whole foods, calling my parents, rest, and giving myself permission to be vulnerable, and IN PROGRESS. 

Being well goes beyond physical health. It’s feeling connected to who you are and the people around you. My goal with @korebyremy and is to provide a catalyst through movement for you to feel rooted in your thoughts and feelings, and move towards your most authentic self and biggest dreams 🧡

Somewhere between then and now, working out to be smaller became stronger, seeking validation turned into believing in myself, perfectionism turned into embracing progress, and a familiar 9-5 turned into building a dream 🦋

The biggest shift this year has challenged me with is learning to command greatness and step into my power, rather than hide behind the fear of failure. Don’t stand in your own way of possibilities bigger than you can imagine✨

Things to do in kauai, hawaii 🌈

A couple tips before we get into the list— check the hours of everything online and on Instagram because a lot of places are based off the surf and closed on the weekend (kind of amazing). Parking for beaches can be tough so rent a smaller car. Also, poké runs out quickly, so go early if you’re planning on getting some for dinner they most likely won’t have. We learned the hard way 🥲

THE LIST: 

Rent a car and explore the island. We stayed on the north shore, which was amazing and would highly recommend.  Everything is on one road, it’s really easy to stop at shops or cafes on your way to and from activities. You can see my other post for favorite food and drink spots!

Relax and enjoy a book and spicy marg poolside at your hotel. We stayed at @1hotel.hanaleibay which speaks for itself. I could’ve stayed there the entire 4 days ngl. They also have onsite activities like sound baths, cooking classes, outdoor and indoor gym with fitness programming, and guided hikes!

Go to the beach, no surprise there. We made it to Lumaha'i (I was scared at the no tourist signs lol), Tunnels, and Hanalei. The Hanalei pier has paddle boards to rent and ride upstream. Note that the parking for Tunnels is tough so go early. We also had a picnic on the hotel’s private beach at sunset and it was magical.

Walk through the towns—we explored Hanalei, Princville, Kapaʻa, and Kilauea. So many cute shops, açaí bowl shacks, fresh fruit stands, markets, all the things. @shipwreckedkauai took all my money 🤙

Go on a boat (or I’ve also heard helicopter) to see the  Nā Pali Coast. You actually feel like you’re in a painting or movie set, it’s too beautiful to be real. We used @napaliexperience for our trip — loved our captain and that she taught us about the cultures of the islands.

Farmers markets!! We sadly didn’t make it to any but drove passed the Princeville one and it looked so fun. There’s also great markets in Kilauea and Hanalei on Saturday’s so I’ve heard.

There’s definitely more to add to this list, but that’s what we were able to do in 4 days. Truly can’t wait to go back 🧜‍♀️

I used to have so much anxiety around vacation —what will I eat, where will I workout, how will I work, what about my routine, what about my plan? 

Reflecting on our incredible trip to Hawaii and how I finally understand that health is beyond fitness and nutrition. It’s fulfillment, connection, and JOY 🌈☀️

Don’t get me wrong, I still move my body and spend time walking and outdoors. I look at these activities as healing for my nervous system and a way to take in my surroundings, rather than part of a strict fitness regimen. 

I try to maintain some sense of routine through online and gym workouts, hot water with lemon, and daily supplements. I eat what feels good for me (which I’ve invested the time to understand what allergies or sensitivities I have) and operate from an INTUITIVE place rather than a restricted.

If you’re like me, you like to plan and feel in control of the where and what during a vacation—with a bachelorette (or trip planned by someone else) that can be tricky. Of course the bride is first and foremost the priority for feeling good, but here’s the list I’ve come up with to help you feel good too! 

— bring snacks that are well balanced like nuts, dried fruit, fruit, sometimes even canned tuna to always have protein on hand. Depending on where you are, food may be limited to specific times and being hangry is a total buzzkill. Also If you go too long without eating, you may cause overeating at meal time, which can be mentally draining & cause stomach discomfort.

— anticipate needing some help with digestion and sleep since a new time zone and environment can throw these things off. I always bring supplements like Theanine & melatonin, digestive enzymes, and magnesium citrate. A packet of chia seeds could also be a good idea to add into some hot lemon water. And also electrolytes, a must!

— communicate any specific need ahead of time such as allergies, not drinking alcohol, sleeping specificities. I have a lot of severe allergies and usually just end up ordering separately. Even if it’s just a food sensitivity, speak up! Your best self isn’t bloated and groggy all weekend. She’s energized and happy 😊 

— bring a book for the pool or beach. This may seem antisocial to some people, but If your social battery is zero and you’re still trying to be present…this is a great way to have some “you” time but also be around everyone. 

— wake up 30 minutes earlier than everyone and go for a walk in the area, resort, hit the gym, spa, whatever you have accessible. This will give you some time to reset for the day, get some movement and/or sunshine in which is so healing!

— it’s not about you, lol. This is a moment to celebrate a special chapter in someone’s life. It’s also a great excuse to connect and get together with friends you maybe haven’t seen in a while. I always always come home having so much fun, there’s really nothing like dressing up and going out with the girls.

Let’s talk eating over the Holidays 🥞🎄🍰🍝

More ever I’m realizing how my relationship with food negatively impacted my ability to be present and enjoy my time while visiting Joey’s family. I used to spend all my of my headspace worrying about the next meal, usually skipping out on breakfast is preparation for the unknown meals ahead, and completely overeating the “healthier” snacks I had packed from home because I was restricting so much. This kept me with a constant stomach ache, anxiety, bloating, and feeling of isolation and homesickness because I just wanted to be home in my routine. 

The truth is, I wasn’t allowing myself the same permission to eat and relax as I did at home because I was so afraid of feeling bad, which ironically I created out of these habits to be “healthy”. What do I do now? I take the pressure off. I eat a very nutrient dense breakfast so I know I won’t be messing with my blood sugar and hunger cues later in the day. I grocery shop and have everything prepped or accessible so I’m not restricting and just not eating. I have a protein, CARB, & fat, in as many meals as I can. I drink when I want, and don’t when I don’t want. I trust myself and my body to tell me what it needs, when it needs. It took me so so long to get here. Here’s what I eat while traveling to keep everything regular 💩

- start your travel day with a full glass of water and celery juice for hydration and help detoxing. For me personally, celery juice on an empty stomach helps flush everything out :)

- bring food with you!! I always make healthier choices when I’ve made it myself or get from my fave @erewhonmarket —chia seed pudding is so easy to bring to-go and has filling healthy fats and fiber from the chia seeds to again, keep things regular 

- anticipate how many hours you will not only be flying and bring meals based on that. For example today we had a 4 hour flight plus 1 hour to drive to airport, 2 hours at the gate, 1 hour to the hotel, etc so we brought breakfast and lunch, and dessert of course ☺️

- bring full balanced meals over snacks. While snacks seem like the convenient and easy choice, it won’t satisfy you the way a full meal will and you may end up overeating and under nourishing. You can bring snacks, just compliment it with real food!

- drink water on the plane, two full water bottles if you can. Sorry to the aisle person next to me, I’m literally out of my seat every hour whoops

- for me, I take @drinklmnt electrolytes and mag citrate before to give my body some assistance, but always talk to a doctor about what works for you!!

This is what I’ve found works for me, hope it helps 💘
